41. vellem. notice that the wish is contrary to the actual fact.

42. virtus: i.e. philosophers in their discussions on virtue. The Stoics are particularly referred to, whose high ideal of virtue and ten- dency to puritanism apparently made them especially inclined to censoriousnesS, and against whom Horace never loses an opportunity to break alance. Cf. v. 96 et seq. - honestum: the Stoic made “the becoming,'’ τὸ πρέπον, i.e. what was in accordance with the nature of man and the universe, the criterion of virtue. Of this expression ho- nestum is the Latin translation, and the word is here used with reference to this technical sense.
